Running Containers Locally with Podman
Objectives
By the end of this lab, you will be able to:

Run containers in both foreground and detached modes
Configure port mapping between host and container
Manage persistent storage using volumes
Override user settings at runtime
Inspect running containers and their configurations
Prerequisites
Linux system with Podman installed (Podman 3.0+ recommended)
Basic understanding of Linux command line
Internet access to pull container images
Setup Requirements
Install Podman if not already present:
sudo dnf install -y podman  # For RHEL/CentOS/Fedora
sudo apt-get install -y podman  # For Debian/Ubuntu
Verify installation:
podman --version
Task 1: Running Containers in Foreground and Background
Subtask 1.1: Run a Container in Foreground
Run a simple container in foreground:

podman run --name foreground-container docker.io/library/nginx
This will start an NGINX container and attach your terminal to it
Expected Outcome: You'll see NGINX logs in your terminal
Terminate the container by pressing Ctrl+C

Subtask 1.2: Run a Container in Detached Mode
Start a container in background:

podman run -d --name background-container docker.io/library/nginx
The -d flag runs the container in detached mode
Expected Outcome: You'll get a container ID but retain terminal control
Verify the container is running:

podman ps
Task 2: Port Mapping and Volume Binding
Subtask 2.1: Bind Container Ports to Host
Map container port 80 to host port 8080:

podman run -d --name webapp -p 8080:80 docker.io/library/nginx
Key Concept: -p HOST_PORT:CONTAINER_PORT maps ports
Verify access:

curl http://localhost:8080
Expected Outcome: You should see the NGINX welcome page
Subtask 2.2: Create Persistent Storage with Volumes
Create a volume:

podman volume create mydata
Run a container with volume mounted:

podman run -d --name vol-container -v mydata:/data docker.io/library/alpine tail -f /dev/null
Verify volume mounting:

podman exec vol-container ls /data
Task 3: User Management and Runtime Overrides
Subtask 3.1: Override User at Runtime
Run a container as specific user:

podman run --rm -it --user 1000 docker.io/library/alpine whoami
Expected Outcome: The command will return "whoami: unknown uid 1000"
For a known user (e.g., nobody):

podman run --rm -it --user nobody docker.io/library/alpine whoami
Expected Outcome: "nobody"
Subtask 3.2: Inspect Running Containers
Get detailed container information:

podman inspect webapp
View container logs:

podman logs webapp
Check resource usage:

podman stats
Task 4: Cleanup
Stop all running containers:

podman stop -a
Remove containers:

podman rm -a
Remove volumes (optional):

podman volume rm mydata
Troubleshooting Tips
If you get "permission denied" errors, try running with --privileged flag
For port conflicts, verify no other service is using the same port with ss -tulnp
If containers exit immediately, check logs with podman logs <container>
Conclusion
In this lab, you've learned essential Podman container management skills:

Running containers in both interactive and detached modes
Configuring network access through port mapping
Implementing persistent storage with volumes
Managing user permissions at runtime
Inspecting container states and configurations
These skills form the foundation for working with containers in development and production environments.

